data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, EF Core's Cosmos DB provider **deprecated** the sync-over-async opt-in (`CosmosOptionsExtension.EnableSyncExecution`). In .NET 11, **it's removed entirely**. Every synchronous LINQ operator and `SaveChanges()` call against the Cosmos DB provider now throws `InvalidOperationException` — there is no workaround other than going async.

**All four methods in your repository break:**

| Call | Why it throws |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | Sync enumeration over Cosmos queries |
| `.First(...)` | Sync single-element query |
| `.Count()` | Sync aggregate query |
| `.SaveChanges()` | Sync persistence |

## The fix — convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks in-memory; no I/O.
- All callers up the chain must also become `async`/`await` (controllers, services, etc.).
- Remove any `EnableSyncExecution` configuration from your `DbContext` setup — the option no longer exists and will cause a compile error.
